The '''Dell Medical School''' is the graduate [[medical school]] of [[The University of Texas at Austin]] in Austin, Texas. The school opened to the inaugural class of 50 students in the summer of 2016 as the newest of 18 colleges and schools on the UT Austin campus.<ref name="About us">{{Cite web|url=https://www.utexas.edu/dell-medical-school/about-us | format= | title=Dell Medical School – About Us | work=utexas.edu | accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> S. Claiborne "Clay" Johnston, [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]], [[Doctor of philosophy|Ph.D.]], was named as the medical school's inaugural [[Dean (education)|dean]] in January 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.utexas.edu/2014/01/21/dell-medical-school-dean | format= | title=Inaugural Dean Named at UT Austin's Dell Medical School | work=utexas.edu | accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>

In accordance with the Medical District Master Plan released in 2013, the University's portion of the medical district is being constructed in three phases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utexas.edu/operations/masterplan/documents/MedicalDistrict20130509.pdf | format=PDF | title=Medical District Master Plan | work=utexas.edu | accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.utexas.edu/2013/05/08/dell-medical-school-construction-plans-unveiled | title=Dell Medical School Construction Plans Unveiled | work=utexas.edu | accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> The new medical campus will sit on existing University property at the southeastern corner of the central campus, adjacent to the existing UT School of Nursing and to the Dell Seton Medical Center at The University of Texas—the new $295 million, 211-bed [[teaching hospital]] that [[Seton Healthcare Family|Seton Healthcare]] is building.<ref name="About us" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seton.net/about_seton/news/2014/04/17/seton_medical_center_at_the_university_of_texas_will_be_name_of_new_teaching_hospital | title='Seton Medical Center at The University of Texas' Will be Name of New Teaching Hospital  | work=seton.net | accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>

In late 2011, Texas Senator Kirk Watson created a list of ten health-care centered goals he hoped to achieve within ten years for his Central Texas district.  Number one on that list was to build a medical school.  In May 2012, the Board of Regents allocated $25 million of annual funding to a UT Austin medical school, plus another $40 million spread over eight years for faculty recruiting.  In November 2012, Travis County voters approved a proposition to raise property tax revenue in support of health care initiatives for Central Texas, including $35 million annually for a medical school.<ref>{{Cite web|title = About Us {{!}} Dell Medical School|url = http://dellmedschool.utexas.edu/about|website = dellmedschool.utexas.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-26}}</ref>

The medical school is named after the [[Michael & Susan Dell Foundation]], which has pledged $50 million over ten years to the school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dellmedschool.utexas.edu/about |format= |title=About Dell Medical School |accessdate=July 9, 2015}}</ref>

